== External links == * [http://j-mediaarts.jp/?locale=en Official Site] {{en icon}}
{{Animation industry in Japan|state=collapsed}}
[[Category:Manga]] [[Category:New media art festivals]] [[Category:Anime and manga awards]] [[Category:Festival organizations]] [[Category:International awards]] [[Category:Art festivals in Japan]] [[Category:Annual events in Japan]] [[category:Arts organizations based in Japan]] [[Category:Awards established in 1997]] [[Category:Festivals established in 1997]] [[Category:Arts organizations established in 1997]] [[Category:1997 establishments in Japan]]

A number of video games were selected by the [[Museum of Modern Art]], located in [[New York City]], as part of its permanent collection. These games were chosen by the Museum of Modern Art in order to showcase design elements within them.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ted.com/talks/paola_antonelli_why_i_brought_pacman_to_moma?language=en |last1= Antonelli|first1=Paola|author-link=Paola Antonelli|title=Why I brought Pac-Man to MoMA |date=May 2013 |publisher=[[TED (conference)|TED]] |accessdate=2014-12-05}}</ref> Fourteen initial games were announced in November 2012, with plans to expand the collection to up to forty games over time, as the museum is able to acquire the display rights for them. Six more games were added to the collection in June 2013, as well a [[home video game console|game console]].
Curated by [[Paola Antonelli]], the collection was included in the exhibition ''Applied Design'' in the [[List of works in the Museum of Modern Art#Department of Architecture and Design|Philip Johnson Architecture and Design Galleries]]. In these galleries, around a hundred objects that represent contemporary design were displayed. Most games in the collection are playable on some level and all are displayed in a manner to minimize the influence of [[nostalgia]].<ref name="PCMag">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2416148,00.asp |title=MoMA Exhibit Showcases Video Games as Modern Art |publisher=''[[PC Magazine]]'' |last=Milot |first=Stephanie |date=2013-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908155956/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0%2C2817%2C2416148%2C00.asp |archive-date=2015-09-08 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref>
==Background== [[File:Pac-Man in the Museum of Modern Art (MOMA).png|thumb|right|alt=A screen on a plain gray wall displaying Pac-Man, with a simple joystick and pair of headphones beneath it|''[[Pac-Man]]'' is placed near the elevator exit, as it was assumed to be one of the most popular games on display.<ref name="Mashable Inside">{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2013/03/01/moma-video-games-exhibit-pics/#_|title=Inside MoMA's Classic Video Games Exhibit|publisher=''[[Mashable]]''|last=Indvik|first=Lauren|date=2013-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908160222/http://mashable.com/2013/03/01/moma-video-games-exhibit-pics/|archive-date=2015-09-08|dead-url=no}}</ref>]]
The exhibition stirred up controversy, as video games are [[Video games as an art form|not commonly considered art]] among critics and therefore might not have a place in an art gallery.<ref name="not art">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2012/nov/30/moma-video-games-art|title=Sorry MoMA, video games are not art|publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|author-link=Jonathan Jones (journalist)|date=2012-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908160418/http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2012/nov/30/moma-video-games-art|archive-date=2015-09-08|dead-url=no}}</ref> However, the collection is modeled after [[Philip Johnson]]’s 1934 exhibition "[[Machine Art]]," in which pieces of machinery such as propeller blades were displayed in a minimalist fashion to lay focus on their [[Mechanical system|mechanical design]]. This set-up would create a "strange distance, this shock, that made people realize how gorgeous formally, and also important functionally, design pieces were," which, according to the exhibit's curator Paola Antonelli, is the desired effect of the exhibition.<ref name="Wired">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2013/05/moma-video-games/|title=‘All Hell Broke Loose': Why MoMA Is Exhibiting ''Tetris'' and ''Pac-Man''|publisher=''[[Wired (website)|Wired]]''|last=Moore|first=Bo|date=2013-05-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908160501/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2013/mar/01/video-games-art-moma-exhibition|archive-date=2015-09-08|dead-url=no}}</ref> In order to minimize factors such as nostalgia, the games are displayed in a minimalist fashion where only a screen and controlling-device are visible on an otherwise blank wall.<ref name="PCMag" />
At least one other video game, namely ''[[Katamari Damacy]]'', has been displayed in MoMA's design galleries before.<ref name="Katamari Damacy" /> The exhibition is part of a movement to include forms beyond traditional media that the Museum of Modern Art began in 2006, starting with [[Typeface|digital font]]s and later moving on to video games. MoMA has taken cautious care of traffic flow, as this had proved to be an "interesting" challenge. Games that are likely to be heavily played, such as ''Pac-Man'', have been placed near entrances and exits to assure a constant flow from these games, while games that would require a larger amount of time to play have had a [[game demo|demo version]] developed for them, so that visitors can beat those and move on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2013/02/27/moma-video-games-exhibit/|title=MoMA Exhibit to Feature 'Pac-Man' and 13 Other Video Game Classics|publisher=''Mashable''|last=Indvik|first=Lauren|date=2013-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908160552/http://mashable.com/2013/02/27/moma-video-games-exhibit/|archive-date=2015-09-08|dead-url=no}}</ref>
Though the MoMA is mainly interested in acquiring a game's hardware and interface, the [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] [[source code]] is considered the most valued. According to Antonelli, "when we cannot acquire the code, we acquire simulations, emulations, the cartridge, the hardware. But what we're interested in showing is the interaction by itself."<ref name="interview1">{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2014-12-15/museum-modern-art-embraces-all-aspects-digital-culture-and-design|title=The Museum of Modern Art embraces all aspects of digital culture and design|publisher=''[[Public Radio International]]''|last=Wernick|first=Adam|date=2014-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911060510/http://www.pri.org/stories/2014-12-15/museum-modern-art-embraces-all-aspects-digital-culture-and-design|archive-date=2015-09-11}}</ref>
The collection leans towards the [[Golden age of arcade video games|classic era]] of [[Arcade game|arcade machine]]s and [[8-bit era|8-bit consoles]] as, during this era, "a small number of visionaries laid the groundwork for where we are now." According to Paul Galloway, many early, "seemingly simple games remain as vital and compelling today as they were" during the 1970s and 80s. [[Ralph H. Baer]]'s [[Magnavox Odyssey]] console was added as it was considered both "a masterpiece of engineering and industrial design" as well as highly important during the birth of the [[video game industry|industry]].<ref name="Magnavox">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/6/28/4475548/moma-adds-magnavox-odyssey-and-six-classics-to-game-design-exhibit|title=MoMA adds Magnavox Odyssey and six classics to game design exhibit|publisher=''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''|last=Campbell|first=Colin|date=2013-06-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908160748/http://www.polygon.com/2013/6/28/4475548/moma-adds-magnavox-odyssey-and-six-classics-to-game-design-exhibit|archive-date=2015-09-08|dead-url=no}}</ref>
==List== The wave indicates when a game was added to the collection; wave 1 was included on {{date|2012-11-29|mdy}}, and wave 2 was included on {{date|2013-06-23|mdy}}. ''Street Fighter II'' was added in November, 2013, and ''Snake'' was added in October, 2015.
