[[File:Sudkovsky 000.jpeg|thumb|200px|Rufin Sudkovsky (1885)]] '''Rufin Gavrilovich Sudkovsky''' (Ukrainian: Руфін Гаврилович Судковський; 19 April 1850, [[Ochakiv]] - 16 February 1885, Ochakiv) Was a Ukrainian painter who specialized in naval and [[Marine art|maritime]] scenes.
== Biography == He was the son of a priest in the Diocese of [[Kherson Governorate|Kherson]]. Originally, he planned to follow in his father's footsteps, studying first at the local religious school, then at the Odessa Theological Seminary,<ref name="W">{{ВТ-ЭСБЕ|Судковский, Руфим Гаврилович}}</ref> but he soon lost interest. He had been attracted to drawing since he was a child, and began to frequent the Odessa Drawing School at the local art society. Under the influence of Odessa's status as a major port, his focus soon turned to maritime themes. [[File:Sudkovsky 003.jpg|thumb|left|275px|Surf at the Pier (1879)]] In 1868, he left the seminary and went to Saint Petersburg, where he was accepted on a provisional basis at the [[Imperial Academy of Arts]]. He eventually became a full student, remaining for three years and being awarded several medals. He returned to Ochakiv in 1871 and began a series of sketches of the [[Black Sea]] coastline.<ref name="W" /> Most of these early works were derivative, and were not successful when they were exhibited in Saint Petersburg. His technique and originality improved during a trip to Germany and France in 1874.<ref name="I">[http://imperiaikon.ru/poleznaya_informaciya/katalog_hudozhnikov/s/sya_mgnoveniya_zdravstvujte_gost_nastroit_katalog_portal_blogi_knigi_znaniya_shkola_menyu_kartiny_foto_vsego_kartin_2463_russkay/ Brief biography] @ Imperia.</ref> Three years later, a new exhibit at the Academy earned him the title of "Free Artist" (second degree). In 1879, he was promoted to first degree.<ref name="W" /> [[File:Sudkovsky 007.jpg|thumb|185px|[[Darial Gorge]] (1884)]]
===Plagiarism?=== He continued to exhibit in Saint Petersburg, sometimes together with [[Julius von Klever]].<ref name="I" /> In 1882, his painting, "Tempest near Ochakiv", won him the title of Academician. The following year, he was married and became embroiled in a controversy when [[Arkhip Kuindzhi]] (a former roommate at the Academy) accused him of plagiarism. Although the critics and press took his side, several artists ([[Ivan Kramskoi|Kramskoi]], [[Vassily Maximov|Maximov]], [[Yefim Volkov|Volkov]] and [[Ilya Repin|Repin]]) published a letter in the ''[[Novoye Vremya (newspaper)|New Times]]'', stating that Sudovsky had "directly borrowed" from Kuindzhi.<ref>[http://museum-painting.dp.ua/ru/painters/painters-ukraine/khudozhniki-ukrainy-xix-nachala-xx-vv/sudkovskij-rufin-rufim-gavrilovich.html Brief biography] @ the Museum of Ukrainian Art, [[Dnipropetrovsk]].</ref>
Two years later, at the height of his career, he fell ill with [[typhus]] during an exhibition in Kiev, and was taken back to Ochakiv, where he died.<ref name="I" /> Despite his short life, he was able to complete a large number of canvases, which were presented by his friends in a retrospective, shortly after his death. His widow, [[Elena Samokysh-Sudkovskaya|Elena]] (also an artist), married the military painter, [[Mykola Samokysh]] in 1889 and became a popular illustrator.<ref name="I" />
